{"questionId":"19884477","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Great Pyramid of Giza has a square base with side lengths of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>440</mn><mo> </mo><mi>REC</mi></math> and a height of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>280</mn><mo> </mo><mi>REC</mi></math>. Viktor assumes that these two measurements are exact and that the Great Pyramid can be modelled as a square-based pyramid with smooth faces.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the minimum possible volume of the pyramid in cubic metres.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1&nbsp; &nbsp;Convert REC to linear metres<br></strong></p>\n<p>attempt to convert REC to metres using their lower bound&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>440</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>×</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>515</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>226</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>OR</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>280</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>×</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>515</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>144</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> seen</p>\n<p>attempt to use the formula for the volume of a right pyramid&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>440</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>×</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>515</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>280</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>×</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>515</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mn>470</mn><mo> </mo><mn>000</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfenced><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mn>468</mn><mo> </mo><mn>106</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>051</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>47</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>×</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2&nbsp; &nbsp;Convert REC to cubic metres</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to use the formula for the volume of a right pyramid&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mn>440</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mn>280</mn></mfenced><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn><mo> </mo><mn>069</mn><mo> </mo><mn>333</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>33</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>attempt to convert 1 cubic REC to cubic metres using their lower bound&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>cubic</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>REC</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo> </mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>515</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mn>440</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mn>280</mn></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>×</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>515</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mn>470</mn><mo> </mo><mn>000</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfenced><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mn>468</mn><mo> </mo><mn>106</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>051</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>47</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>×</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong><em>[4 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19884477","referenceCode":"23N.1.SL.TZ1.2b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the minimum possible volume of the pyramid in cubic metres.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, midpoints","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.6—Approximating and estimating"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}